lesex, England":"Enfield, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Bridgwater, Somerset, England":"Bridgwater, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wroth","type":"LAST","meanings":["Anglo-Saxon: Wradh, wrath, anger"],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Wroth II was born in 1390, in Enfield, Middlesex, England, his father, John WROTH, was 41 and his mother, Margaret Willington, was 29. He married Amery Averia de Mortimer in 1415, in Enfield, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1444, in Enfield, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54, and was buried in Bridgwater, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1390–1444":"1390–1444","1393–1434":"1393–1434","1425–1480":"1425–1480","1450–1487":"1450–1487","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1361–Female":"1361–Surnud","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","abt 1434":"umbes 1434","1434":"1434","1444":"1444","1487":"1487","1450":"1450","1361":"1361","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1480":"1480","1390":"1390","Enfield, Middlesex, England":"Enfield, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bridgwater, Somerset, England":"Bridgwater, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1390–1444":"1390–1444","1393–